.TH "WHOAMI" 7 "February 2026" "atomdns handlers" "atomdns authors"

.SH "NAME"
.PP
\fIwhoami\fP \- return your resolver's local IP address, port and transport

.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
The \fIwhoami\fP handler is not really that useful, but can be used for having a simple (fast) endpoint
to test clients against. When \fIwhoami\fP returns a response it will have your client's IP address in
the additional section as either an A or AAAA record.

.PP
The reply always has an empty answer section. The port and transport are included in the additional
section as a SRV record, network can be "tcp" or "udp".

.PP
If the \fIecs\fP handler added an address to the context, \fIthat\fP address is used instead.

.PP
.RS

.nf
\&.\_<network>.qname. 0 IN SRV 0 0 <port> .

.fi
.RE

.PP
The \fIwhoami\fP handler will respond to every A or AAAA query, regardless of the query name.

.SH "SYNTAX"
.PP
.RS

.nf
whoami

.fi
.RE

.SH "EXAMPLES"
.PP
Start a server on the default port and load the \fIwhoami\fP handler.

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org {
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
When queried for "example.org A", atomdns will respond with:

.PP
.RS

.nf
;; QUESTION SECTION:
;example.org.   IN       A

;; ADDITIONAL SECTION:
example.org.            0       IN      A       10.240.0.1
\_udp.example.org.       0       IN      SRV     0 0 40212

.fi
.RE
